”%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c At around 1:50 in the video, however, they interview the mother of some of the students, whose vernacular is more definitively AAVE; it seems her children had to code switch to cope and it stuck with them. One of the first things she said was “My kids was tested and was put into special ed classes,” which according to standard American English (and google docs) is ungrammatical. I’d wager it’s tiny differences like these that are quite simple to understand, at least in hindsight here in 2021, would make ill-informed, perhaps closet-racist teachers turn a blind eye to these students back in the 1970s. Fortunately, when the issue was brought to court, attorney Ken Lewis won it for the students.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Interestingly, this court case was used as precedent for another one in Oakland, CA years later. In it, they referred to AAVE as ebonics, and even defined it as an entirely separate language. In discussing the case, Ken Lewis (interviewed in the video) seems to advocate for code switching. When the white interviewer asks him whether, were someone to come into his law firm talking like Puff Daddy, Ken amicably chuckles and without a trace of caution in his tone says “The reality is that he has to fit the criteria, the skills, for the particular job… If I were to be an R&B radio announcer, I’d have to change my own language skills.” What do you think of his response? What distinguishes a dialect from language skills in your opinion?%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:section: B:)%0a%3c (:Category: 